DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2007.01279.x
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 2405
EP  - 2443
VL  - 62
IS  - 5
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2007.01279.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT Using responses to a well-known confidential survey, we study corporations' use of derivatives to ?take a view? on interest rate and currency movements. Characteristics of speculators suggest that perceived information and cost advantages lead them to take positions actively; that is, they do not speculate to increase risk by ?betting the ranch.? Speculating firms encourage managers to speculate through incentive-aligning compensation arrangements and bonding contracts, and they use derivatives-specific internal controls to manage potential abuse. Finally, we examine whether investors reading public corporate disclosures are able to identify firms that indicate speculating in the confidential survey; they are not.
ER  - 

